This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of Natural Language Processing (cs.CL) because it deals with multi-document summarization, which is a common task in NLP. It also involves the use of consensus-based techniques, which are often used in NLP research. 

It could also belong to the Information Retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category because summarization is a common task in IR, and the paper discusses the use of pseudo-relevant summaries to estimate the performance of individual candidate systems. 

The paper's focus on ensemble systems and leveraging the strengths of individual systems suggests that it could also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. 

The use of rankings and the proposed content-based approach could also place this paper in the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. 

Finally, the use of datasets and experiments suggests that this paper could also belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category.
